The first symbol of any string derived from the grammar must come from the left-hand child of one of the three start-rules  

 S → NT17 NT21 | S → NT26 NT18 | S → NT2 NT10.

To generate the given string, that left-hand child has to yield the first token t26.

• NT17 can only begin with NT1 or NT7, and none of their possible derivations can produce t26 (both ultimately start with t48, t24, t52, t29, t9, … but never t26).  
 → NT17 cannot start the string.

• NT2 can only begin with NT18; NT18 starts with NT14, NT10, NT21 or t12.  
 The only route that can make t26 is the long chain  
  NT18 ⇒ NT14 NT27 ⇒ NT26 NT27 ⇒ NT4 NT8 … with NT4 ⇒ NT16 NT6 ⇒ t26 …  
 but the very next symbol would have to come from NT6, whose leftmost output can only be t29, t9, t47, t2, … never t13 (the second token of the string).  
 → NT2 cannot match the first two tokens.

• NT26 can start with t26 via NT26 ⇒ NT4 NT8 with NT4 ⇒ NT16 NT6 and NT16 ⇒ t26.  
 Again the next token must come from NT6, and NT6’s leftmost possibilities (t29, t9, t47, t2, …) never include t13.  
 → NT26 cannot match the first two tokens either.

Since none of the only three possible left children of S can produce the required prefix “t26 t13”, the string cannot be derived from the grammar.
